194
00:15:55,120 --> 00:15:59,040
Well, I'm going to go back to the Edward Tufte 
quote that I use all the time, which is design is  

195
00:15:59,040 --> 00:16:04,080
clear thinking made visible. And so I think most 
people when they talk about design, they think  

196
00:16:04,080 --> 00:16:09,680
of it as the visual expression of an idea. They 
think of it as a team or a function or a group.  

197
00:16:09,680 --> 00:16:15,520
I think of it as a holistic mindset. When design 
thinking became big, I was always really confused  

198
00:16:15,520 --> 00:16:20,960
because I didn't know how else you could think. 
That was just how I naturally thought, which is  

199
00:16:20,960 --> 00:16:26,960
design is trying to imagine the future you want to 
live in and then take the steps to make it real. 

200
00:16:26,960 --> 00:16:31,920
It's living with a certain type of 
intentionality in almost a Buddhist type way,  

201
00:16:31,920 --> 00:16:36,400
which is different from science, which is 
observational trying to understand. It's  

202
00:16:36,400 --> 00:16:39,680
a little bit different from engineering, which 
is we kind of know where we want go at the end,  

203
00:16:39,680 --> 00:16:45,200
but we're trying to go one step at a time 
versus design's trying to see some further  

204
00:16:45,200 --> 00:16:51,680
out future state and account for a larger or 
a different set of constraints and issues than  

205
00:16:51,680 --> 00:16:56,960
engineering or some of the other problem solving 
methodologies. Again, I look at it as a company,  

206
00:16:56,960 --> 00:17:02,800
does the company think in a design mindset and 
Apple does, Airbnb does. I don't get the sense  

207
00:17:02,800 --> 00:17:07,040
that Google does and I don't get the sense 
that Amazon does. That's not a critique on  

208
00:17:07,040 --> 00:17:12,000
them. I don't think that those organizations are 
competing on design in the same way. But again,  

209
00:17:12,000 --> 00:17:19,360
I want to go work at a place that as an 
organization thinks in a design type method.

210
00:17:19,360 --> 00:17:24,800
Along those lines, a lot of people imagine 
every founder, every product builder is just,  

211
00:17:24,800 --> 00:17:28,480
yes, I'd love amazing design. I'd love 
our products to be incredibly beautiful,  

212
00:17:28,480 --> 00:17:33,200
intuitive, so easy for everyone to use and 
understand, but they don't actually invest  

213
00:17:33,200 --> 00:17:38,000
in these areas and they don't put a lot 
of resources into the designing process.  

214
00:17:39,680 --> 00:17:44,160
What's the best pitch you can make and 
that you do make to companies to help  

215
00:17:44,160 --> 00:17:50,640
them see the strategic value of design 
and the bottom of the value of design.

216
00:17:50,640 --> 00:17:54,320
Let me back up and just dissect a little bit 
the way you described design, you described it  

217
00:17:54,320 --> 00:17:59,520
in really tactical terms. You said beautiful, 
intuitive products that make sense. I think it  

218
00:17:59,520 --> 00:18:04,800
was something like that. What you were describing 
was you were describing the part of the iceberg  

219
00:18:04,800 --> 00:18:10,080
that sits above the water line, which is the 
result. That's one of the outcomes of design,  

220
00:18:10,080 --> 00:18:15,200
but that's not the real heavy lifting of design. 
Design is more like liberal arts or philosophy  

221
00:18:15,200 --> 00:18:20,240
or something. It's like what do we try to 
achieve at a much lower level? And so what  

222
00:18:20,240 --> 00:18:24,480
I talk to founders and people about the value of 
design, what I'm pushing them on is when we can  

223
00:18:24,480 --> 00:18:29,360
get organizational alignment around what we want 
to do philosophically, why do we exist? What's  

224
00:18:29,360 --> 00:18:33,760
the vision for the company? How do all these 
things ladder up through vision, through mission,  

225
00:18:33,760 --> 00:18:38,560
through specific tenets, design strategies.
And then into actual execution. How do we  

226
00:18:38,560 --> 00:18:44,080
ladder that whole thing up so it makes sense 
as a whole? That's the magic of design. The  

227
00:18:44,080 --> 00:18:47,920
difference is when you design things, you end 
up with a bunch of bricks that are piled into  

228
00:18:47,920 --> 00:18:53,040
