00:29:36,160 --> 00:29:40,640
what didn't work for me in those particular 
organizations. I'll go back to what I said,  

366
00:29:40,640 --> 00:29:44,480
every company's different, every culture is 
slightly different. It's not one size fits all. 

367
00:29:45,120 --> 00:29:48,800
I point out the idea of design reporting 
to engineering just because I don't think  

368
00:29:48,800 --> 00:29:54,160
people consider the possibility often enough. So 
there's three options, design is its own thing,  

369
00:29:54,160 --> 00:29:58,480
design is part of product, design is part of 
engineering. And I think there's a moment when  

370
00:29:58,480 --> 00:30:03,440
you can back up and make an intelligent choice 
about the pros and cons for each of those options  

371
00:30:03,440 --> 00:30:09,680
inside your org. And so I would encourage people 
to just take a design mentality and put on that  

372
00:30:09,680 --> 00:30:13,600
designer mindset just for a moment and say, well, 
what's the thing that we're trying to produce?  

373
00:30:13,600 --> 00:30:18,480
What's the incentives that we're trying to create? 
What's the future state that we're trying to get  

374
00:30:18,480 --> 00:30:24,800
to? And which of these three options, permutations 
is going to help us get there the best?

375
00:30:24,800 --> 00:30:28,640
I love how radical this idea 
is. I've not heard it. I think  

376
00:30:28,640 --> 00:30:34,320
designers will be like, " You stop it. 
Just stop it." So have you operated  

377
00:30:34,320 --> 00:30:37,840
this way? Have you had design report to 
engineering in companies you've worked at?

378
00:30:38,880 --> 00:30:42,880
Sorry, but that's how it worked at Apple the 
whole time under Steve. Design always reported  

379
00:30:42,880 --> 00:30:48,320
to engineering. Now I think it's structured a 
little bit differently, but design has always  

380
00:30:48,320 --> 00:30:53,440
been part of engineering at Apple, so I saw 
it work quite effectively there obviously.

381
00:30:53,440 --> 00:30:57,280
It's so interesting. Okay, so say just to 
give someone something very tactical to do  

382
00:30:57,280 --> 00:31:01,360
on their team, say they don't want to go 
to this extreme and move the design org  

383
00:31:01,360 --> 00:31:04,720
under engineering, what's something 
you've seen work that helps achieve  

384
00:31:04,720 --> 00:31:09,520
similar outcomes with having engineers 
integrated early in the design process?

385
00:31:09,520 --> 00:31:14,000
Yeah, look, I think you have to find some way 
that you are able to identify a few people in  

386
00:31:14,000 --> 00:31:17,840
engineering that I refer to as creative 
technologists. So these are people that  

387
00:31:17,840 --> 00:31:22,880
can come into what's ultimately kind of a fairly 
airy-fairy philosophical discussion about what  

388
00:31:22,880 --> 00:31:27,760
we could do and what's right from a conceptual 
model perspective. Ultimately, it's sort of a  

389
00:31:27,760 --> 00:31:35,360
philosophy issue. And there's not that many PMs 
or engineers that can sit in that space and be  

390
00:31:35,360 --> 00:31:40,320
comfortable with the ambiguity of it all. A PM's 
likely going to come in and they're going to say,  

391
00:31:40,320 --> 00:31:44,400
okay, well that was a great one hour. What's the 
next step? And as a designer I'm always like,  

392
00:31:44,400 --> 00:31:46,640
well, the next step is we're going to have 
another meeting and we're going to talk  

393
00:31:46,640 --> 00:31:50,640
again. And the engineers oftentimes when 
they're starting to hear different ideas,  

394
00:31:50,640 --> 00:31:54,080
they're already cutting into the code and they're 
trying to figure out what's hard and what's easy. 

395
00:31:54,080 --> 00:31:58,240
And so I think the trick is at the beginning, 
can you find a small group of people from  

396
00:31:58,240 --> 00:32:03,760
the different functions that can sit with the 
ambiguity of the space and talk through a broad  

397
00:32:03,760 --> 00:32:08,640
range of ideas to identify the direction we want 
to go into? And then once everybody kind of falls  

398
00:32:08,640 --> 00:32:13,040
in love with the direction, then you can go into 
the more tactical mindset of, okay, well, when we  

399
00:32:13,040 --> 00:32:17,040
can ship it and who can we show it to and how are 
we going to code it and when's it going to go live  

400
00:32:17,040 --> 00:32:21,920
and all those sorts of things. But the trick is 
to try to find a group that can sit, again, in the  

401
00:32:21,920 --> 00:32:27,520
ambiguous maybe space. I do think it's critical to 
have everybody together at the beginning so they  

402
00:32:27,520 --> 00:32:32,560
all feel like they're part of it. And the worst 
thing is when you bring something fully baked...  

403
00:32:32,560 --> 00:32:36,320
Well, the worst thing when you bring something 
fully baked to anybody for their approval. 

404
00:32:36,320 --> 00:32:40,880
We could talk about this when you take a final 
design to an exec and an exec sees it for the  

405
00:32:40,880 --> 00:32:44,720
first time in a high resolution state, I'll 
get to that in a second. But when you go to  

406
00:32:44,720 --> 00:32:48,160
an engineering team says, "Hey, we've been working 
in the lab for six months and we have this thing  

407
00:32:48,160 --> 00:32:52,800
that we love it and we just can't wait for you 
guys to build it, and here it is," I don't know,  

408
00:32:52,800 --> 00:32:57,360
[inaudible 00:32:54] mention here. They're going 
to be excited about. They're not order takers.  

409
00:32:57,360 --> 00:33:02,640
How do you make them part of the process? And 
every product of consequence that I worked on,  

410
00:33:02,640 --> 00:33:06,800
there was some moment when we were showing it 
to some critical person and you could see that  

411
00:33:06,800 --> 00:33:10,960
they fell in love with it. Sometimes they're 
literally pointing at the comps on the board,  

412
00:33:10,960 --> 00:33:14,160
sometime you're in a meeting and they're 
just like, "God, I just love this." 

413
00:33:14,160 --> 00:33:20,160
And for me, that was always the critical moment 
because I knew that design can't bring you this  

414
00:33:20,160 --> 00:33:25,520
stuff into the world on its own. We can't raise 
this baby, we need the village, and we need the  

415
00:33:25,520 --> 00:33:30,720
village to fall in love with the baby. And so 
until that happens, you're not really quite sure  

416
00:33:30,720 --> 00:33:36,720
if this thing's going to take off or not. And so 
it was always extremely important to me that you  

417
00:33:36,720 --> 00:33:41,040
had a few key engineers and some product people 
fall in love with it so they could defend it and  

418
00:33:41,040 --> 00:33:46,240
embrace it and enhance it and add to it. And you 
got to bring them along at the very beginning.

419
00:33:46,240 --> 00:33:49,040
What I'm hearing there is there's 
a big part of just buy-in and  

420
00:33:49,040 --> 00:33:52,800
then there's also just obviously 
more good ideas early are great.

421
00:33:52,800 --> 00:33:57,520
Yeah, sorry. Buy-in doesn't feel quite 
right to me, because buy-in feels like, oh,  

422
00:33:57,520 --> 00:34:05,200
I've come to agree with you. And that's different 
from it's a part of me. When I'm talking to teams,  

423
00:34:05,200 --> 00:34:10,000
the thing I try to tell them is, I walk into 
the office every day with the idea that everyone  

424
00:34:10,000 --> 00:34:14,480
that I work with is fundamentally a 
maker. Everybody in product design,  

425
00:34:14,480 --> 00:34:18,400
engineering, we've all chosen these 
careers. Everybody's super smart,  

426
00:34:18,400 --> 00:34:21,760
everybody's super ambitious. Everybody 
could have done a thousand other things,  

427
00:34:21,760 --> 00:34:27,760
but they're choosing to spend their precious 
lifetime and creative energy creating software. 

428
00:34:27,760 --> 00:34:31,600
And so I believe in my heart that they're 
all fundamentally makers. And the thing  

429
00:34:31,600 --> 00:34:35,680
that I know about makers is that they all want 
to make something they're proud of so they can  

430
00:34:35,680 --> 00:34:39,520
take it home at the end of the day and show it 
to their parents and say, "Look at what I made  

431
00:34:39,520 --> 00:34:43,920
at school with my friends today." That's the 
fundamental thing, and they're all doing it  

432
00:34:43,920 --> 00:34:47,200
from their own different points of view and 
their own different incentives and mindsets,  

433
00:34:47,200 --> 00:34:51,280
but they all at the end of the day want to make 
something they're proud of. And so it's not a  

434
00:34:51,280 --> 00:34:59,520
matter of getting their buy-in, it's a matter 
of them being a part of it. I don't know, it's  

435
00:34:59,520 --> 00:35:06,000
a part of their soul in a really deep, meaningful 
way. And I'm not sure you can graph that onto  

436
00:35:06,000 --> 00:35:11,840
somebody after the fact. They kind of need to be 
there at the moment of inception, if you will.

437
00:35:11,840 --> 00:35:18,160
Wow, that's a really beautiful answer. I 
imagine for a lot of people hearing this,  

438
00:35:18,160 --> 00:35:21,520
making every feature and product they 
build a part of their soul feels like a  

439
00:35:21,520 --> 00:35:26,160
very high bar if they're building 
some kind of B2B SaaS software.  

440
00:35:26,160 --> 00:35:33,120
So I guess just thoughts in just how much you 
should spend, how much time, how many resources,  

441
00:35:33,120 --> 00:35:36,560
how deep you go on design for all these things 
you're building. Say you're building some kind of,  

442
00:35:36,560 --> 00:35:43,520
I don't know, expense management system or 
HRS thing, just like, what do you recommend  

443
00:35:43,520 --> 00:35:49,600
people do with, in terms of just how far to go 
in design as a lever, as a differentiator maybe?

444
00:35:49,600 --> 00:35:53,840
Well, inherent in your question is this assumption 
that design takes more time. And so I'm going to  

445
00:35:53,840 --> 00:35:58,960
kind of reject that premise, because I don't think 
design takes more time. I think design exists.  

446
00:35:58,960 --> 00:36:03,600
There is going to be a design. It's whether it's 
going to be a good one or not. And I think there's  

447
00:36:03,600 --> 00:36:09,440
things that you can do so that you're able to 
operate it at a quicker pace as design. Again, if  

448
00:36:09,440 --> 00:36:13,360
you get the... We haven't talked about tenets yet, 
but we'll get to that in a moment. If you kind of  

449
00:36:13,360 --> 00:36:17,440
create a shared philosophical understanding 
of the product and what you're trying to do,  

450
00:36:17,440 --> 00:36:22,000
you can go really fast because you're not asking 
the question of what should you do, you're asking  

451
00:36:22,000 --> 00:36:26,640
the question of, what would this company with 
what we stand for do for this thing? And that's  

452
00:36:26,640 --> 00:36:30,800
a much easier question that's much smaller.
So if you look at the companies that have the  

453
00:36:30,800 --> 00:36:35,520
largest design teams, they're often the companies 
that have the most ambiguous cultures and the most  

454
00:36:35,520 --> 00:36:41,120
unclear design vision. When you go to companies 
that really know what they're doing and they're  

455
00:36:41,120 --> 00:36:44,960
clear that this is who we are, this is what 
we stand for, the design teams are super small  

456
00:36:44,960 --> 00:36:48,560
because they're not sitting there trying to do 
all these permutations with color and typography  

457
00:36:48,560 --> 00:36:54,400
and ideas. They're operating in a really narrow 
vein, because they know who they are. It's very  

458
00:36:54,400 --> 00:36:58,640
much like individuals. When you're a teenager 
or a young adult, you can spend a lot of time  

459
00:36:58,640 --> 00:37:01,680
trying to figure out what to wear because 
you haven't really sorted it out yet. But  

460
00:37:01,680 --> 00:37:06,000
by the time you get to be a little bit older, 
you've kind of got your personal style, and so  

461
00:37:06,000 --> 00:37:10,960
dressing in the morning gets to be a lot easier.
Like at Pinterest. I was at Pinterest at a point  

462
00:37:10,960 --> 00:37:16,400
when Pinterest wasn't quite sure who it was. And 
so when we were going to do an onboarding flow,  

463
00:37:16,400 --> 00:37:20,960
we had to look at a really broad sweep of things, 
because we were trying to sort it out. But you  

464
00:37:20,960 --> 00:37:25,680
had other places that knew what they were about, 
Apple's the key example there, we weren't trying  

465
00:37:25,680 --> 00:37:28,800
to figure out what it was about. We were trying 
to figure out what was the apple way to do this  

466
00:37:28,800 --> 00:37:33,440
particular thing, and so that moves a lot faster.
And I agree, look, having your soul at every  

467
00:37:33,440 --> 00:37:39,760
little checkbox sounds like a high bar and in some 
ways it is. I think you need to be able to back  

468
00:37:39,760 --> 00:37:45,520
up and look at the product, maybe not at every 
state, but generally every six months or a year,  

469
00:37:45,520 --> 00:37:51,440
you need to back up and ask yourself, am I proud 
of this? Is this something I am happy to be a part  

470
00:37:51,440 --> 00:37:57,760
of? Do I believe in this? Is it a representative 
of my best work given the circumstances I was in,  

471
00:37:57,760 --> 00:38:00,960
which has limitations around time 
and resources and everything else,  

472
00:38:00,960 --> 00:38:06,240
is this the best I could do or am I just sort of 
trying to get through the day I have other goals?

473
00:38:06,240 --> 00:38:10,400
So let's actually follow the thread 
of design tenets and principles.  

474
00:38:10,400 --> 00:38:14,960
This is something I've heard about you, 
that you're a big fan of design tenets  

475
00:38:14,960 --> 00:38:19,920
versus design principles. What is the 
difference? Why is this so important?

476
00:38:19,920 --> 00:38:23,440
Yeah, so look, there's whole websites dedicated to 
design principles, and if you go and you read it,  

477
00:38:23,440 --> 00:38:30,560
you'll see a lot of principles like simple, clear, 
beautiful, fast, secure. You'll hear these words  

478
00:38:30,560 --> 00:38:33,760
and all these words are great. I mean, obviously 
I have nothing against any of these words,  

479
00:38:33,760 --> 00:38:39,520
but they're not useful as decision-making tools 
because nobody would ever argue the opposite.  

480
00:38:39,520 --> 00:38:43,760
Nobody ever sat in a meeting and said, "Oh, 
forget clear. Let's try to make it as confusing as  

481
00:38:43,760 --> 00:38:49,440
possible." So the idea of clear, it's nice to have 
out there as, I don't know, sort of a platitude to  

482
00:38:49,440 --> 00:38:53,680
move towards, but I just don't think it helps 
you make decisions. And so tenets are really  

483
00:38:53,680 --> 00:38:59,520
decision-making tools and it's sort of like... A 
classic one is paper versus plastic. It's just too  

484
00:38:59,520 --> 00:39:03,760
complicated to reconsider that every time you're 
at the grocery store. So you sort of make a rule  

485
00:39:03,760 --> 00:39:07,520
for yourself and you're just a paper person 
or a plastic person, you move on from there. 

486
00:39:07,520 --> 00:39:12,400
And so it's sort of that at scale. And the story 
comes from when they were starting to work on  

487
00:39:12,400 --> 00:39:17,120
Keynotes, apparently the guy who was responsible 
for originating Keynote went to Steve and said,  

488
00:39:17,120 --> 00:39:22,400
"How should we think about Keynote?" And Steve 
said, "I want you to keep three things in mind.  

489
00:39:22,400 --> 00:39:27,280
One is it should be difficult to make ugly 
presentations. Two, you should focus on  

490
00:39:27,280 --> 00:39:32,480
cinematic quality transitions. And three, you 
should optimize for innovation over PowerPoint  

491
00:39:32,480 --> 00:39:37,680
compatibility." And if you take that last one in 
particular, if he hadn't kind of said, we're going  

492
00:39:37,680 --> 00:39:41,840
to go this way instead of that way, that team 
would've spent the next 10 years gouging each  

493
00:39:41,840 --> 00:39:48,160
other's eyes out over whether they should try to 
go for PowerPoint compatibility or innovation. And  

494
00:39:48,160 --> 00:39:53,440
so when I was at ThoughtSpot, I realized pretty 
early on that I wasn't going to be able to have  

495
00:39:53,440 --> 00:39:56,720
any sort of command and control over everything 
that was going to happen in the product. 

496
00:39:56,720 --> 00:40:00,800
There was too many people involved, too many 
engineering teams, most of them were in India.  

497
00:40:01,360 --> 00:40:07,520
I needed to move from a mindset of control to 
one of choreography. I needed to try to set  

498
00:40:07,520 --> 00:40:12,080
the culture and set certain design tenets 
that everyone could internalize and follow  

499
00:40:12,080 --> 00:40:17,520
and hopefully then make the right decisions in 
that groove, if you will. And so we had three,  

500
00:40:17,520 --> 00:40:20,640
I think you can't have more than three or four 
because you need everybody to memorize them.  

501
00:40:21,680 --> 00:40:28,720
They can't be consulting a handbook. And so, one 
of them was documentation is a failure state. In  

502
00:40:28,720 --> 00:40:31,440
enterprise companies, a lot of times people 
think, "Oh, we'll just put it in the manual.  

503
00:40:31,440 --> 00:40:35,440
It'll be part of the training." And I would 
constantly be coming back and go, "Stop it.  

504
00:40:35,440 --> 00:40:41,520
Nobody wants to learn our software. Nobody cares. 
We are just one more browser tab in a world of  

505
00:40:41,520 --> 00:40:46,320
browser tabs. We are not this user's complete 
world. They do not want to learn this stuff." 

506
00:40:46,320 --> 00:40:51,280
Documentation's a failure state. Maybe we can't 
always avoid it, but we should do everything we  

507
00:40:51,280 --> 00:40:56,160
can to simplify things so you can figure it out 
in the context of the product. That's number one.  

508
00:40:56,160 --> 00:41:00,720
Number two is every interaction should start 
simple and the users should have to opt into  

509
00:41:00,720 --> 00:41:06,160
complexity. So our main competitor at the time was 
Tableau. Tableau started with complexity. That was  

510
00:41:06,160 --> 00:41:10,000
their whole value prop is like, "We're a super 
powerful tool. We can do all sorts of stuff."  

511
00:41:10,000 --> 00:41:14,400
So when you sit down at Tableau, it feels like 
you're flying the space shuttle. And if you're a  

512
00:41:14,400 --> 00:41:18,560
professional data analyst, that's great. That's 
the kind of tool you wanted. That wasn't what  

513
00:41:18,560 --> 00:41:22,080
ThoughtSpot was about. We were trying to take 
data analytics into the hands of what I call  

514
00:41:22,080 --> 00:41:26,720
mere mortals, also known as business users, people 
who didn't live in breathe this stuff every day. 

515
00:41:26,720 --> 00:41:29,840
So our goal with them was they could sit 
down and it was an approachable piece of  

516
00:41:29,840 --> 00:41:33,600
software and they could turn on all the bells 
and whistles and power if they wanted it,  

517
00:41:33,600 --> 00:41:38,640
so that was the second one. Start simple, let the 
users opt into complexity. And the third one was  

518
00:41:38,640 --> 00:41:43,600
the entire product should look and feel like it 
came from a single mind. And this was a tenet to  

519
00:41:43,600 --> 00:41:48,160
try to combat the natural tendency of enterprise 
companies to really fragment because you have all  

520
00:41:48,160 --> 00:41:51,840
these different teams working on their incentive 
to work just on their little piece. And so they  

521
00:41:51,840 --> 00:41:55,040
think about what's right for them and they 
don't back up to look at the whole thing. 

522
00:41:55,040 --> 00:41:59,280
And so we had this tenet, the whole thing should 
look and feel like it came from a single mind to  

523
00:41:59,280 --> 00:42:03,600
just try to remind people, how does this fit into 
the whole system? And sometimes we need to go  

524
00:42:03,600 --> 00:42:07,680
along and do things that work for the product that 
don't necessarily work quite the way we might want  

525
00:42:07,680 --> 00:42:13,040
them to for our feature. And so those tenets were 
all... Again, they were all decision-making tools.  

526
00:42:13,040 --> 00:42:16,480
And when we would have design debates, we could 
just come back to this, wait, are we actually  

527
00:42:16,480 --> 00:42:21,360
starting simple and forcing them to opt into 
complexity or are we doing something else here?

528
00:42:21,360 --> 00:42:26,320
So there's kind of this implication in 
this discussion about tenets is that you  

529
00:42:26,320 --> 00:42:31,520
need to be very opinionated. There's a clear 
here's what's in and here's what's out. Is  

530
00:42:31,520 --> 00:42:35,280
there anything more along those lines and 
are there other tenet examples you could  

531
00:42:35,280 --> 00:42:39,600
share to give people some inspiration as 
they think about their potential tenets?

532
00:42:39,600 --> 00:42:44,880
It's very context specific, so it's a little bit 
like what are your tenets for parenting? It's a  

533
00:42:44,880 --> 00:42:50,320
very specific personal type thing that's germane 
to your particular context. So I'm not sure if I  

534
00:42:50,320 --> 00:42:54,000
have a lot of other examples, and I haven't 
heard this used by a lot of other companies,  

535
00:42:54,000 --> 00:42:58,560
so I haven't been able to add a bunch of 
stuff. We tried to come out with tenets  

536
00:42:58,560 --> 00:43:03,040
for individual features and we had trouble 
with that. It felt like they operated at  

537
00:43:03,840 --> 00:43:07,680
sort of the design strategy level. And I 
just think that varies dramatically from  

538
00:43:07,680 --> 00:43:13,520
company to company. What I would look for is 
if you're a design leader or a product leader,  

539
00:43:13,520 --> 00:43:17,520
try to pay attention to what are the debates 
that we keep having over and over where people  

540
00:43:17,520 --> 00:43:23,440
kind of seem to be digging in and things sort 
of seem to be bifurcating into two camps. 

541
00:43:23,440 --> 00:43:28,080
And then is there something we can do where 
we just have that debate once and for all,  

542
00:43:28,080 --> 00:43:32,000
we decide as an organization, we're going left 
instead of right, and you're absolutely correct.  

543
00:43:32,000 --> 00:43:38,320
You have to be opinionated, but that's how 
you're going to win. There's no unopinionated  

544
00:43:38,320 --> 00:43:41,680
software that's been successful. You have 
to have a point of view. The question is,  

545
00:43:41,680 --> 00:43:46,720
what's it going to be? So I'd say practically 
