00:58:44,240 --> 00:58:48,560
A few months ago, I guess a little longer ago, 
I was talking to the team at Toast who makes  

726
00:58:48,560 --> 00:58:52,240
the handheld point of sale stuff that they use 
in restaurants. And the thing I was trying to  

727
00:58:52,240 --> 00:58:59,200
tell them, is whether or not you see it, tonight, 
you're going to be at dinner with a few 100 000  

728
00:58:59,200 --> 00:59:03,520
people all across the country. And if we take 
just one example, you're going to be at a very  

729
00:59:03,520 --> 00:59:09,280
nice diner with a grandmother and her two teenage 
sons in Ohio, and the check's going to come and  

730
00:59:09,280 --> 00:59:13,680
the waiter, the waitress is going to hand over the 
device to that grandmother, because she wants to  

731
00:59:13,680 --> 00:59:18,080
pick up the bill. And you have the opportunity 
to either make her look like a superhero,  

732
00:59:18,080 --> 00:59:22,160
because she knows what she's doing, or to make her 
look like a fool and one of her teenage grandsons  

733
00:59:22,160 --> 00:59:26,400
is going to grab the device and do it for her.
You're at the dinner table, what are you going  

734
00:59:26,400 --> 00:59:30,400
to do for grandma? You going to show up as well as 
you can, or are you going to just let this whole  

735
00:59:30,400 --> 00:59:34,400
thing fall apart, because you didn't think hard 
enough about grandma? And that's true for Toast,  

736
00:59:34,400 --> 00:59:40,080
that's true for every product any 
of us are working on all the time.

737
00:59:40,080 --> 00:59:45,440
This is so interesting and fascinating and 
inspiring. I was going to ask how you use  

738
00:59:45,440 --> 00:59:51,040
this insight, that software is kind of the most 
powerful medium media more than even than TV and  

739
00:59:51,040 --> 00:59:55,600
movies, and you shared it, which I think is really 
important. So just to kind of double-down on this,  

740
00:59:55,600 --> 01:00:01,440
is the advice here is think about the emotion 
you want the user of your software to have as  

741
01:00:01,440 --> 01:00:04,640
you're starting the design process, 
not just what do you want them to do,  

742
01:00:04,640 --> 01:00:09,520
how fast do you want them to get to this flow, 
it's what's the emotion you want them to have?

743
01:00:09,520 --> 01:00:12,240
Yeah. I often don't think about what I 
want them to do. I just think that's sort  

744
01:00:12,240 --> 01:00:19,360
of a selfish way to think about it. They 
have something they want to do. I'm trying  

745
01:00:19,360 --> 01:00:26,000
to help them. I just don't ever approach these 
things of the user's something for me to exploit  

746
01:00:26,000 --> 01:00:30,480
and take advantage of and manipulate. I know 
there's people that do approach it that way,  

747
01:00:30,480 --> 01:00:36,000
which I think is a little unfortunate. But 
as a designer, I guess I have my own set of  

748
01:00:36,000 --> 01:00:40,960
values and my own kind of compass on these 
things that's pushed me in a certain way of  

749
01:00:40,960 --> 01:00:44,640
thinking about it. And so I'm kind of constantly 
asking what's the right thing for the user? 

750
01:00:44,640 --> 01:00:50,400
And I believe in my heart that if we prioritize 
that wonderful things will happen for all the  

751
01:00:50,400 --> 01:00:55,520
metrics, including the money metrics that matter. 
I've never seen a product be successful that  

752
01:00:55,520 --> 01:01:00,080
used metrics as a driver for what they were 
doing. I've seen a lot of companies be really  

753
01:01:00,080 --> 01:01:05,120
successfully seeing metrics as a consequence and 
a way to evaluate the quality of their decisions,  

754
01:01:05,120 --> 01:01:09,200
and then using those to triangulate and make 
better decisions moving forward. So they're  

755
01:01:09,200 --> 01:01:15,840
kind of a very useful feedback mechanism. But 
I think there's definitely a risk to confusing,  

756
01:01:15,840 --> 01:01:20,000
doing something because it's a driver 
versus something as a consequence.

757
01:01:20,000 --> 01:01:23,360
There's a few more questions I would ask, 
but I want to come back to something that  

758
01:01:23,360 --> 01:01:27,200
I asked earlier, that I think is on the minds 
of a lot of say founders and product managers  

759
01:01:27,200 --> 01:01:32,000
listening to this. I'm just like, okay, this 
all is sounds really great. I would love to  

760
01:01:32,000 --> 01:01:38,240
make these experiences so great. It's going 
to take us a lot of time to do this really,  

761
01:01:38,240 --> 01:01:42,880
really well. You said that it doesn't 
have to. What's a tactical tip or two  

762
01:01:42,880 --> 01:01:48,320
that you can suggest to a founder or 
product manager to help them contain  

763
01:01:48,320 --> 01:01:52,960
the design process while also achieving 
these outcomes that you're describing?

764
01:01:52,960 --> 01:01:57,840
Well, I think if you can give... Maybe one 
way to think about it is like a big giant  

765
01:01:57,840 --> 01:02:02,320
AI prompt. The more context you can give 
it, the more specificity you can give it,  

766
01:02:02,320 --> 01:02:06,160
the more this is what I'm about and what we're 
trying to get to, the more the designer's  

767
01:02:06,160 --> 01:02:10,560
going to be able to figure out which swim lane 
they're supposed to be in to produce something. 

768
01:02:10,560 --> 01:02:16,240
So I think if you're going into it feeling like 
the design process is going to take a lot of time,  

769
01:02:16,240 --> 01:02:22,160
it's because you haven't been clear in your 
creative brief, so to speak, which often means  

770
01:02:22,160 --> 01:02:25,840
you're not really clear in your own head. And I 
think... I have worked with a lot of founders,  

771
01:02:25,840 --> 01:02:29,520
and we could identify a bunch of big companies, 
who I think got started that weren't clear in  

772
01:02:29,520 --> 01:02:35,040
their own head. I don't want to... Yahoo was an 
amazing company, but if we just look at Yahoo for  

773
01:02:35,040 --> 01:02:39,680
a second, I worked there, it was never clear 
to me what the founding vision of Yahoo was. 

774
01:02:39,680 --> 01:02:44,640
And I talk a lot about vision statements and 
we could say the vision statement of Google is  

775
01:02:44,640 --> 01:02:49,200
organizing all the world's information. That's a 
great vision. They'll never achieve that. That's  

776
01:02:49,200 --> 01:02:53,440
something that's always over the horizon. And 
it's been a very useful organizing principle for  

777
01:02:53,440 --> 01:02:58,160
their acquisitions and how the company grows.
Amazon to be the Earth's most customer-centric  

778
01:02:58,160 --> 01:03:02,400
company. Okay, great. That's a vision, they will 
never get there. It tells you how they're going  

779
01:03:02,400 --> 01:03:07,280
to expand. Apple doesn't have an explicit 
vision, but I might describe it as personal  

780
01:03:07,280 --> 01:03:12,160
computing can have a transformative effect on 
the lives of individuals. And I think that kind  

781
01:03:12,160 --> 01:03:16,880
of focuses a lot of what they're trying to do.
Disneyland, still the best vision statement of  

782
01:03:16,880 --> 01:03:21,600
all time, which is the happiest place on earth. 
So once you tell an employee this is supposed  

783
01:03:21,600 --> 01:03:25,760
to be the happiest place on earth, then you're 
signaling all sorts of things about how they need  

784
01:03:25,760 --> 01:03:30,880
to pick up the trash and how they need to show up 
on time and how they need to wear their uniform.  

785
01:03:30,880 --> 01:03:34,720
You're just signaling a whole bunch of stuff.
So when I talked to founders, a lot of times  

786
01:03:34,720 --> 01:03:38,160
they just don't have that clarity of what's the 
vision of the company. And to go back to Yahoo  

787
01:03:38,160 --> 01:03:42,160
for a second, I never heard of vision. And so I'm 
not really sure what they were ever about. They  

788
01:03:42,160 --> 01:03:45,200
kind of stumbled into the directory and then 
they added a bunch of stuff around the edges,  

789
01:03:45,200 --> 01:03:49,680
but it never seemed to make a lot of sense. 
And so I think people operating inside Yahoo,  

790
01:03:50,880 --> 01:03:54,160
it ended up being inefficient, because they 
were having to deal with all that ambiguity. 

791
01:03:54,160 --> 01:03:56,960
So I think that that can also be a 
pretty big risk for founders. They  

792
01:03:56,960 --> 01:04:01,040
end up caught up with a product idea, and 
they think that the company is the product,  

793
01:04:01,040 --> 01:04:04,560
the company is not the product. The product 
is the product and the company's bigger than  

794
01:04:04,560 --> 01:04:10,640
the product. And you need to have some vision 
that speaks beyond just this particular thing. 

795
01:04:11,760 --> 01:04:18,400
I think Slack, honestly, both Slack and 
Pinterest I think are examples of products  

796
01:04:18,400 --> 01:04:22,960
that became companies, but neither one of those 
places really knew what to do next, because they  

797
01:04:22,960 --> 01:04:28,720
didn't have a bigger vision of the change they 
were trying to see in the world. So back to you,  

798
01:04:28,720 --> 01:04:32,880
you were asking a very pragmatic question. I 
think you need to work on your prompt before  

799
01:04:32,880 --> 01:04:38,080
you go to your designers and try to give them 
as much clarity about what you want to produce  

800
01:04:38,080 --> 01:04:44,240
as possible. And I think if you leave it open as 
to the emotional response you want users to have,  

801
01:04:44,240 --> 01:04:49,040
you're inviting a lot of ambiguity, which 
is going to invite a lot of inefficiency.

802
01:04:49,040 --> 01:04:56,560
I love that answer. And it's so interesting that 
AI can help us work better together as humans,  

803
01:04:56,560 --> 01:05:01,520
because when you find that the AI is 
not achieving the outcome you want  

804
01:05:01,520 --> 01:05:06,880
as effectively as you want, that's a lesson. 
This also translates the working with humans,  

805
01:05:06,880 --> 01:05:12,880
make the prompt more specific, add more context 
in life, not just when you're talking to AI.

806
01:05:12,880 --> 01:05:13,280
Yeah.

807
01:05:13,280 --> 01:05:17,840
I love that. That's so interesting. So 
the advice here is, if you're finding  

808
01:05:17,840 --> 01:05:23,600
design is taking too long or you want to just 
level up your success with your design team,  

809
01:05:23,600 --> 01:05:27,440
give more context, spend more time on the 
brief, on what you're actually trying to  

810
01:05:27,440 --> 01:05:32,560
achieve. And make sure there's a clear vision 
or mission that everyone can row towards.

811
01:05:32,560 --> 01:05:36,560
Yeah. Look, design is a problem solving 
methodology. So the more variables you  

812
01:05:36,560 --> 01:05:40,640
can remove before they go into the process, 
the more efficient it's going to be. And if  

813
01:05:40,640 --> 01:05:45,360
you give designers a lot of ambiguity, they're 
going to spend a lot of time spinning around,  

814
01:05:45,360 --> 01:05:50,560
and honestly, that's your fault as the client.
As a design leader, I think one of my main  

815
01:05:50,560 --> 01:05:56,160
challenges is frankly trying to make the 
PMs better clients, helping them get more  

816
01:05:56,160 --> 01:06:01,520
specific. It's very common for a design team to 
get extremely ambiguous asks from a product team.  

817
01:06:01,520 --> 01:06:05,360
And the problem for designers, they have to take 
all that ambiguity and they've got to wring it all  

818
01:06:05,360 --> 01:06:08,640
out. So when they give it to engineering, 
engineering knows exactly what to code,  

819
01:06:08,640 --> 01:06:13,040
because computers don't tolerate ambiguity. 
Engineers need to know what the thing's going  

820
01:06:13,040 --> 01:06:19,600
to be. And so design gets stuck with a really 
ambiguous input, but they have to have a highly  

821
01:06:19,600 --> 01:06:26,400
specific output and then often timeboxed to do 
that. And it's just not a recipe for success. 

822
01:06:26,400 --> 01:06:31,360
So you're much better off either kind of 
compressing the PRD experience and bringing  

823
01:06:31,360 --> 01:06:35,520
the designers into that, kind of co-creating 
with product and design really rapidly. But  

824
01:06:35,520 --> 01:06:40,080
you need to... You could think of it in some ways 
as designers are going to draw the storyboards,  

825
01:06:40,080 --> 01:06:43,760
and if you don't give them a great script, 
they're going to have a very hard time.  

826
01:06:43,760 --> 01:06:48,480
And then you can't give the shooting crew 
ambiguous storyboards or you're just going  

827
01:06:48,480 --> 01:06:53,200
to waste untold amounts of money on set.
So if you think about those three steps  

828
01:06:53,200 --> 01:06:58,240
from script to storyboard to production, 
it's all about getting rid of ambiguity.  

829
01:06:58,240 --> 01:07:03,760
And so the more ambiguity that can be removed 
upstream, the faster design's going to go.

830
01:07:03,760 --> 01:07:08,880
This begs the question then, you don't want to 
give designers here exactly. Here's the thing  

831
01:07:08,880 --> 01:07:15,040
we're designing, make it really great and pretty. 
There's always this balance of just give designers  

832
01:07:15,040 --> 01:07:20,560
space to think and be creative and explore. 
Advice there of just how to navigate that.

833
01:07:20,560 --> 01:07:25,120
Well, if you go back to my example of the script 
and storyboard, scripts don't contain pictures,  

834
01:07:25,120 --> 01:07:28,880
there's still a lot of opportunity 
to think differently and to come up  

835
01:07:28,880 --> 01:07:32,720
with original things and to have a lot 
of creative input in the storyboarding  

836
01:07:32,720 --> 01:07:39,360
process. So the script is living mostly in 
words, which is largely how PMs function. 

837
01:07:39,360 --> 01:07:44,240
The thing that I will say, to keep in mind 
for PMs, there's always a tendency on PMs to  

838
01:07:44,240 --> 01:07:48,320
want to draw something and then try to give 
a sketch to a designer. And I would caution  

839
01:07:48,320 --> 01:07:52,560
them against that. Sometimes they have to 
draw themselves so they can think it out.  

840
01:07:52,560 --> 01:07:58,880
But if a PM came to me with something 
that was drawn and kind of fully baked,  

841
01:07:58,880 --> 01:08:02,960
my response was like, thanks for giving me 
that. Now I know exactly what we're not going  

842
01:08:02,960 --> 01:08:08,960
to do. Because as a point of pride, there's no 
way I'm going to go execute that exact thing. 

843
01:08:08,960 --> 01:08:13,520
So you're right, PMs have to give you the 
space to operate. And I think a lot of what  

844
01:08:13,520 --> 01:08:18,960
they're trying to achieve could be done in more 
informal ways, conversationally and whiteboards,  

845
01:08:19,680 --> 01:08:27,280
things like that. But yet you need to narrow the 
problem for the designers, they need constraints.  

846
01:08:28,720 --> 01:08:35,120
They don't need a tiny little box, but they need 
constraints. Think in terms of, you don't give  

847
01:08:35,120 --> 01:08:39,280
them an airport tarmac and you don't even 
give them a football field. You give them  

848
01:08:39,280 --> 01:08:45,520
something more like a basketball court, a sort 
of scale at which they can do their design thing.

849
01:08:45,520 --> 01:08:50,560
I want to talk about basketball later, 
but not yet. You've shared a lot of  

850
01:08:50,560 --> 01:08:54,800
counterintuitive lessons on building 
product, designing, building teams,  

851
01:08:54,800 --> 01:09:00,400
leadership. Is there another very counterintuitive 
lesson you've learned about building products,  

852
01:09:00,400 --> 01:09:04,160
hiring leading teams that goes 
against common startup wisdom?

853
01:09:04,160 --> 01:09:09,360
The thing I would say is that you should 
wait as long as possible to draw a picture.  

854
01:09:11,120 --> 01:09:15,360
I think that pushes against all the gen AI 
tools that help you create prototypes. And  

855
01:09:15,360 --> 01:09:19,440
there's obviously a lot of excitement around 
that. I can just give a prompt and the AI,  

856
01:09:19,440 --> 01:09:23,920
they're going to crank out of UI for me.
So I don't think I'm using the term right,  

857
01:09:23,920 --> 01:09:28,720
but I had this idea from art that I call the 
primal mark, and that's the first mark that  

858
01:09:28,720 --> 01:09:32,640
you make on the canvas. And once you make 
that mark on the canvas, everything you do  

859
01:09:32,640 --> 01:09:38,320
after that is in response to that mark. It 
sort of sets your baseline. And so for me,  

860
01:09:38,320 --> 01:09:43,760
I always felt that as soon as we drew a 
picture that looked even remotely real,  

861
01:09:43,760 --> 01:09:48,480
everybody gravitated towards that and said, oh, 
that's the thing. And people were so uncomfortable  

862
01:09:48,480 --> 01:09:54,080
with ambiguity that they can't really deal with 
the tension of, well, that might not be the thing. 

863
01:09:54,080 --> 01:10:00,080
And so as soon as you draw a picture that looks 
even slightly realistic, much less something that  

864
01:10:00,080 --> 01:10:04,480
comes out of one of these gen AI tools, everybody 
kind of goes, oh, that's the thing. You just keep  

865
01:10:04,480 --> 01:10:09,760
doubling down on that thing. And what's happened 
is you've taken the possibilities from this big  

866
01:10:09,760 --> 01:10:14,800
broad thing down to this tiny little thing from 
an AI system that's trained on existing solutions  

867
01:10:14,800 --> 01:10:19,680
and existing ideas and is maybe not even thinking 
about it the right way, because all you've really  

868
01:10:19,680 --> 01:10:24,320
given it is your first-order of thinking.
I think there's a way you can stay in these  

869
01:10:24,320 --> 01:10:29,280
things conceptually and conversationally, 
where you can get to your second, third,  

870
01:10:29,280 --> 01:10:33,600
fourth idea. And that's where stuff gets really 
interesting. And again, I don't think that has to  

871
01:10:33,600 --> 01:10:37,520
take a lot of time. That can be over the course 
of a single meeting, you could get to a second,  

872
01:10:37,520 --> 01:10:42,560
third, fourth idea. You just have to be willing 
to not jump at the first thing that looks like a  

873
01:10:42,560 --> 01:10:45,440
possibility. You get that possibility, 
you go, okay, well that's interesting,  

874
01:10:45,440 --> 01:10:48,640
let's table that. What else have we got?
There's one story that kind of related  

875
01:10:48,640 --> 01:10:54,160
that's useful. In one of my previous jobs, I was 
responsible for the public website. I remember  

876
01:10:54,160 --> 01:10:58,000
coming across one of the product managers one day 
and she's like, "Hey, this link on the home page,  

877
01:10:58,000 --> 01:11:01,040
we have to make it blue." I was like, "Well, we 
don't use blue links anywhere." And she said,  

878
01:11:01,040 --> 01:11:03,360
"Yeah, yeah, but we just have to make it 
blue." I was like, "Well, we're not making  

879
01:11:03,360 --> 01:11:07,680
it blue." And a couple of days go by and I saw 
the home page and the link had been made blue,  

880
01:11:07,680 --> 01:11:11,040
because she had got around me and she'd 
gone to engineering and just made it blue. 

881
01:11:11,040 --> 01:11:14,320
And I saw her in the hallway again. I was like, 
"What the hell's up with that?" And she goes,  

882
01:11:14,320 --> 01:11:16,480
"Well, people couldn't see it." And 
I'm like, "Oh, they couldn't see it,  

883
01:11:16,480 --> 01:11:19,520
so it wasn't prominent enough, right?" She's like, 
"Yeah, it wasn't prominent enough." I'm like,  

884
01:11:19,520 --> 01:11:24,160
"Well, great. There's a 100 different things 
we could do to make it more prominent, one of  

885
01:11:24,160 --> 01:11:30,400
which is making it blue, which is the thing that 
came to you first because you're not a designer,  

886
01:11:31,040 --> 01:11:34,160
it's naturally... Because it's the most obvious 
thing, but it actually doesn't fit in with  

887
01:11:34,160 --> 01:11:38,800
these larger things we're trying to do."
So I've often... I try to encourage the  

888
01:11:38,800 --> 01:11:44,720
product managers to what's the problem with the 
thing? And then let us solve it. Don't jump to  

889
01:11:44,720 --> 01:11:49,200
it and tell us... Don't tell us this is just 
exactly what we're supposed to do. And again,  

890
01:11:49,200 --> 01:11:54,720
I do the same thing on the roadmap. You decide 
the roadmap, tell us what we're supposed to do,  

891
01:11:54,720 --> 01:11:59,200
I will ask you about it, and I may push back 
and we may have some back and forth, but that's  

892
01:11:59,200 --> 01:12:02,480
your responsibility. I'm going to trust that you 
are trained and you know what you're doing and  

893
01:12:02,480 --> 01:12:06,640
you're going to make the right call. And I just 
want you to give me the same level of respect.

894
01:12:06,640 --> 01:12:12,560
This advice about not drawing quickly and not 
making that primal mark, which I love that term,  

895
01:12:12,560 --> 01:12:18,400
is, I'm curious your take on AI prototyping tools 
these days. Because that's the extreme version of  

896
01:12:18,400 --> 01:12:22,000
that. Not only are you just creating a sketch, 
it's like, oh, it's working, here it is. Here's  

897
01:12:22,000 --> 01:12:27,280
what it looks like. Thoughts on that, do you 
discourage people from doing that, PMs especially?

898
01:12:27,280 --> 01:12:31,520
Well, I think it's a production tool. Once 
you know what you want and you can give it a  

899
01:12:31,520 --> 01:12:35,920
really robust prompt, then... I haven't played 
with it a lot myself, because I'm not in an  

900
01:12:35,920 --> 01:12:40,320
operational role right now, but presumably it's 
really useful at cranking out that actionable  

901
01:12:40,320 --> 01:12:45,120
prototype which you can click and experience.
And I've said for a long time that an interactive  

902
01:12:45,120 --> 01:12:48,960
idea needs to be expressed interactively, so 
we're not talking with our hands and we can really  

903
01:12:48,960 --> 01:12:53,440
understand what's going to happen. So when the 
idea is ready to be expressed, I think those tools  

904
01:12:53,440 --> 01:12:59,280
are probably fantastic. But ideas start off pretty 
fragile, and the best ideas start off really  

905
01:12:59,280 --> 01:13:05,680
fragile. And I think when you push them to develop 
too quickly and you put them out in the world and  

906
01:13:05,680 --> 01:13:09,760
expect them to be able to stand up to critique 
too early, you're just going to squash them. 

907
01:13:09,760 --> 01:13:15,360
I often think about them like the little plant 
in the Pixar movie, Wall-E, you've got to give  

908
01:13:15,360 --> 01:13:19,440
that little guy a little space, a little time, 
some water and some nourishment, and you can't  

909
01:13:19,440 --> 01:13:23,040
really just suddenly put him out in the wind and 
think he's going to make it. And so I think a lot  

910
01:13:23,040 --> 01:13:28,960
of... There's a lot of very fragile, interesting, 
quiet ideas that I think you need to give some  

911
01:13:28,960 --> 01:13:32,960
space. And when you jump to the expression 
of them, I think you're putting them at risk. 

912
01:13:32,960 --> 01:13:38,480
I'll also say that, everybody, when they look at a 
prototype, what they're focusing on is the visual  

913
01:13:38,480 --> 01:13:44,080
and textual expression. And so as soon as you 
produce something in high resolution the feedback  

914
01:13:44,080 --> 01:13:48,880
you're going to get is going to be about colors 
and shapes and these presentation layer things,  

915
01:13:48,880 --> 01:13:57,120
which are very loosely related to usability 
and value. It's like focusing on the special  

916
01:13:57,120 --> 01:14:02,240
effects of a movie that has a really bad story.
And so at ThoughtSpot, we used to use what we  

917
01:14:02,240 --> 01:14:06,800
call block brain diagrams, which were even 
simplified versions of wire frames. It was  

918
01:14:06,800 --> 01:14:10,560
just big chunky blocks of here's how the screen 
could be and where things might be located. And  

919
01:14:10,560 --> 01:14:16,160
because it was so low fidelity, people couldn't 
get into commenting on what it looked like. We  

920
01:14:16,160 --> 01:14:19,840
had to talk about conceptually what it was. 
And so we were trying to build up this firm  

921
01:14:19,840 --> 01:14:24,640
foundation where we could go from the block frames 
to wire frames to kind of the final expression. 

922
01:14:24,640 --> 01:14:29,280
And I think it helped us clarify what we were 
trying to do conceptually so that by the time  

923
01:14:29,280 --> 01:14:33,920
we got to the final visual presentation, that 
stuff was actually really simple. And initially  

924
01:14:33,920 --> 01:14:38,320
it made the product team really nervous because 
we would be sitting in these block frames and  

925
01:14:38,320 --> 01:14:42,320
wire frames for sometimes weeks, and they'd be 
like, when are we finally going to see the comps? 

926
01:14:42,320 --> 01:14:47,120
And then what would happen, is because we had such 
a robust design system, once we locked down on the  

927
01:14:47,680 --> 01:14:53,120
block frames, we could send it to an agency and 
they could do the full high-res comps in a day,  

928
01:14:53,120 --> 01:14:56,400
because they knew exactly what they were 
doing. And so the PMs were always like,  

929
01:14:56,400 --> 01:15:00,240
what the hell happened overnight? You're like, 
well, it turns out that the high-res stuff,  

930
01:15:00,240 --> 01:15:04,480
that's not the hard thing. The hard thing is the 
heavy lifting of thinking, what are we really  

931
01:15:04,480 --> 01:15:07,680
trying to do? That's the hard part.
And if you do the high-res stuff,  

932
01:15:07,680 --> 01:15:13,360
you really muddy the waters. And I think you 
end up spending a lot more time churning,  

933
01:15:13,360 --> 01:15:16,640
if you didn't... Again, I'm going to go back 
to the movie metaphor, because I studied  

934
01:15:16,640 --> 01:15:22,480
film. If you're trying to fix script issues 
when you're in production or storyboarding,  

935
01:15:22,480 --> 01:15:26,480
you're going to churn and you're going to waste 
a lot of effort. So you've got to figure out  

936
01:15:26,480 --> 01:15:30,720
what you're trying to do before you go draw the 
high-res stuff. And I think a lot of the gen AI  

937
01:15:30,720 --> 01:15:35,760
tools, it's this seductive thing of, hey, let's 
just go, let's go make the comp and see what we  

938
01:15:35,760 --> 01:15:41,600
think. I don't really know if you're going to 
get anything great out of that process, maybe.

939
01:15:41,600 --> 01:15:43,920
That's a really interesting counter-narrative  

940
01:15:43,920 --> 01:15:48,320
because it feels like every team now is just 
straight to prototypes. I just had the C...  

941
01:15:48,320 --> 01:15:54,400
She's one of the CPOs at Microsoft. I realize 
there's many CPOs, and she has this concept of  

942
01:15:55,200 --> 01:15:59,680
demos before memos and just prompt sets or 
any PRDs, you should just be prototyping  

943
01:15:59,680 --> 01:16:04,080
all your ideas. And so it's interesting to 
hear the perspective of maybe it's actually  

944
01:16:04,080 --> 01:16:10,000
hurting your ability to come up with a really 
clever solution versus the obvious solution.

945
01:16:10,000 --> 01:16:13,200
Yeah. Look, I think at some point, hopefully 
people just back up and ask themselves,  

946
01:16:13,200 --> 01:16:17,120
are we actually producing better product 
because of this process? And we're going faster,  

947
01:16:17,120 --> 01:16:22,000
but faster can't be the ultimate goal. You 
need to be creating something great as well,  

948
01:16:22,000 --> 01:16:26,320
right? Something that's sustainable and frankly 
that you're proud of and your users find value  

949
01:16:26,320 --> 01:16:31,520
in. And if you're just throwing so much spaghetti 
at the wall, I don't know if having a spaghetti  

950
01:16:31,520 --> 01:16:37,120
throwing machine that goes faster is...
Look, there's a counter argument that's...  

951
01:16:37,120 --> 01:16:40,320
You can say, oh, it's like Darwinian evolution, 
and we're just going to spin through a bunch of  

952
01:16:40,320 --> 01:16:45,840
random mutations and see what happens. And 
I used to joke that it's true, that if you  

953
01:16:45,840 --> 01:16:49,840
take a bunch of hydrogen atoms and give them 14 
billion years, you could end up with a tiger,  

954
01:16:49,840 --> 01:16:52,960
but you don't know you're going to get a tiger 
and you could get a six headed shrimp instead,  

955
01:16:52,960 --> 01:16:56,960
and you don't really know when it's going 
to shift. So I'm not exactly sure Darwinian  

956
01:16:56,960 --> 01:17:02,240
evolution is the way we create great product, 
but a lot of companies are making a run at it.

957
01:17:02,240 --> 01:17:08,160
I want to take us to a recurring segment on 
